00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:21.580
So this is how the HarvEst story goes.

00:04:21.580 --> 00:04:26.580
In 1985, on a sunny
day by the Sather Gate,

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:30.593
two Berkeley freshmen from
Hong Kong met by fate.

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:35.000
Harvey and Esther, or
when the names combine,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.960
better known as HarvEst,

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.243
were passionate about studying economics.

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:46.030
Harvey took Econ 1 from
Professor Laura Tyson,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:49.163
while Esther got Professor Freeman.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:54.930
And before you knew it,
the HarvEst seed was sown

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:58.263
and started to blossom in Wheeler Hall.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
So today, 30 years later,
HarvEst returns to Cal,

00:05:05.780 --> 00:05:09.070
with their little HarvEst, Kisha and Tika,

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:12.490
to celebrate the 1985 vintage.

00:05:12.490 --> 00:05:16.533
But more importantly, to pay
tribute to their Alma Mater.

00:05:18.170 --> 00:05:21.750
So Harvey and I are really
honored to be here today

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:23.630
to host the second series

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:27.403
of the HarvEst Distinguished
Women Leader Lecture Series.

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:32.090
We are very honored that our guest speaker

00:05:32.090 --> 00:05:34.690
is Professor Laura Tyson,

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:38.440
who actually was Harvey's
first economics professor,

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:40.920
and she was the one who inspired Harvey

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:43.030
to major in economics,

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:46.223
who in turn inspired me to follow suit.

00:05:48.070 --> 00:05:52.620
There's a saying that
women hold up half the sky.

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:56.500
Well, being a full-time mom,
and being a full-time owner

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:58.310
of my own public relations company,

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:01.310
I must say that most of
the time I have to hold up

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:02.880
more than half of a company,

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:05.190
and more than half of the family.

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:08.400
And you know, men are normally considered

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:10.900
as the bread winners of the family,

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.720
while women are the pillars of the family,

00:06:13.720 --> 00:06:16.830
having to take care of
so many household chores,

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:21.390
kid's education, financial
planning, logistics management,

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:24.420
signing checks, and entertaining guests.

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:26.220
So how do we do it all, right?

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:29.570
It really takes someone with good

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:33.360
time management and multitasking skills.

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:36.430
And I will say, women are
actually quite fortunate

00:06:36.430 --> 00:06:38.670
to be born with the talent of

00:06:38.670 --> 00:06:41.090
good time management and prioritization,

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:44.850
especially for super achievers
like Professor Tyson,

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:48.080
who also writes books,
who also does research,

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:52.050
who also gives speeches, like today,

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:56.480
and who also advises the
President of the United States.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:59.150
She indeed is a role model.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:00.690
Speaking of role model,

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:02.460
over the years that I've been involved

00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:05.510
with a lot of women related
business organizations,

00:07:05.510 --> 00:07:10.460
and charity organizations,
I've been telling all my 25

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:14.060
mentees that it's very important to find

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:18.930
a good role model or a mentor for life.

00:07:18.930 --> 00:07:20.310
Someone who can share with you

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:23.250
their experiences and their insights.

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:27.920
Someone who can inspire
women to empower themselves.

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:30.760
And I think it's very
important that these days,

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:33.790
we as women, have to empower ourselves,

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:37.270
and then have to nurture
our leadership skills

00:07:37.270 --> 00:07:39.320
to give back to the community.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.350
And this is indeed the inspiration

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:44.260
behind our endowment of
HarvEst Distinguished

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.270
Women Leader Lecture Series,

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:48.850
and as Dean Doyle mentioned earlier,

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:51.950
the series was launched
back in October of 2013,

00:07:51.950 --> 00:07:54.810
and we were very honored to
have Mrs. Harriet Fulbright

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:56.600
as our inaugural speaker,

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:58.880
who delivered an enlightening speech

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:01.420
on international education.

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:05.660
And I think you know through
prominent speakers sharing,

00:08:05.660 --> 00:08:09.490
we hope that this lecture
series will be able to elevate

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:13.470
the status of women from a socioeconomic,

00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:17.170
professional, and personal aspect,

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:20.570
just to let women live up to

00:08:20.570 --> 00:08:23.400
my favorite four Ps framework,

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:25.500
which is P for passion.

00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:28.120
I think it's very important for someone,

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:30.720
for yourself to find your passion.

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:33.940
To really find what you love doing,

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:37.180
and then to live your
dreams to the fullest.

00:08:37.180 --> 00:08:39.950
The second P is for positivity.

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:43.140
This word I use a lot to
teach my kids, Kisha and Tika.

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:45.130
I say, always think positive.

00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:46.040
Don't think negative.

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:50.270
Always think of a glass being
half full and not half empty.

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:53.210
Because positivity breeds happiness,

00:08:53.210 --> 00:08:56.980
it breeds self-confidence,
it breeds success.

00:08:56.980 --> 00:08:59.960
And the third P is for perseverance.

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:04.790
Don't let anything come in
the way to achieve your goal.

00:09:04.790 --> 00:09:08.540
It's all about will power,
all about discipline.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:11.110
And I always, you know
my favorite case study

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:15.080
is to share my own
experience in overcoming

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:18.220
three miscarriages within four years.

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:22.420
But I told myself, at
least I'm conceivable.

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.450
I know one day I'm gonna be a mother.

00:09:24.450 --> 00:09:26.740
So now I have two beautiful daughters.

00:09:26.740 --> 00:09:29.340
And the fourth P is for philanthropy.

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:32.120
Philanthropy meaning giving
back to the community,

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:34.040
giving back to your Alma Mater,

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:36.360
because there are so many unfortunate

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:38.240
and underprivileged people out there

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:39.900
who need our help.

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:42.010
So Harvey and I are really excited today

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:45.770
that we're going to learn
about the fifth P, politics.

00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:46.603
(light laughter)

00:09:46.603 --> 00:09:49.710
How politics, or policy making,

00:09:49.710 --> 00:09:54.710
will empower women in the
workplace, and in the family,

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:57.520
and in turn add value to the economy.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:09:59.853
Let us welcome Professor Laura Tyson.

00:10:00.769 --> 00:10:01.850
(applause)

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:06.470
Our honorable guest speaker
who will be speaking

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:09.500
on Women's Work in the World Economy

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:12.732
from a Political and Personal Perspective.

00:10:12.732 --> 00:10:13.565
(applause)

00:10:13.565 --> 00:10:14.528
Thank you.

00:10:14.528 --> 00:10:16.778
(applause)

00:10:18.348 --> 00:10:20.765
(whispering)

00:10:31.446 --> 00:10:33.060
- Thank you, Esther, you and Harvey

00:10:33.060 --> 00:10:36.162
are truly inspirational in your vision for

00:10:36.162 --> 00:10:38.823
endowing this lecture series.

00:10:40.690 --> 00:10:43.120
Without further ado,
it's my great pleasure

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:47.740
to introduce my colleague,
Professor Laura Tyson.

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:52.740
You have biographical
notes, and Laura said,

00:10:52.747 --> 00:10:55.087
"Please don't spend too
long introducing me."

00:10:56.590 --> 00:11:00.975
She says, "Basically, I've
been here a very long time."

00:11:00.975 --> 00:11:03.050
(laughs)

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:06.503
Professor Tyson joined the
Berkeley faculty in 1977.

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:10.300
She's been on the faculty,

00:11:10.300 --> 00:11:13.680
at the Haas School of Business since 1990,

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:15.210
and she was the dean

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:19.057
of the School of Business from 1998-2001.

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:23.500
In addition, as Esther mentioned,

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:27.860
she has advised Presidents
of the United States.

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:30.380
She's the former chair
of the US President's

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:32.400
Council of Economic Advisor,

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.000
and former director of the
National Economic Council

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
under the Clinton administration.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.940
She was the first woman to
hold both of these roles.

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:43.600
And more recently, she served
on President Barack Obama's

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:45.470
Economic Recovery Advisory Board,

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:50.192
so we can thank Laura for
the improving global economy.

00:11:50.192 --> 00:11:51.490
(light laughter)

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:55.120
Without further ado, I'm
gonna welcome to the stage,

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:57.757
my colleague, and ask you to do similarly.

00:11:57.757 --> 00:12:00.007
(applause)

00:12:03.064 --> 00:12:04.731
- I appreciate that.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:12.010
Well good afternoon everyone.

00:12:12.010 --> 00:12:14.477
It's really, it's a honor to be here.

00:12:14.477 --> 00:12:17.280
The University of
California Berkeley has been

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:20.950
a major part of my life
for a very long time.

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:25.850
It's actually very inspiring
to actually meet students

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:27.840
who I once taught many years ago.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:32.390
I was asked when I was in
Washington the first time,

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:35.430
with President Clinton, I had a knack

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:38.240
for making economics fairly simple.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:39.927
So people would say to me constantly,

00:12:39.927 --> 00:12:42.047
"Where did you get the training

00:12:42.047 --> 00:12:44.610
"to make economics fairly simple?"

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:47.520
And I said, well, a lecture hall

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:51.640
of 800 freshmen and
sophomores who you had to

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:54.860
keep awake, and keep engaged.

00:12:54.860 --> 00:12:56.240
And that was my best training.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:58.830
So the university has been
extremely important to me,

00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:01.870
and I'm very, very thankful to welcome

00:13:01.870 --> 00:13:03.390
Esther and Harvey back,

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:06.000
and to realize that I'm connected to them

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.603
in that very personally important way.

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:11.700
I'm gonna talk about Women's Work

00:13:11.700 --> 00:13:13.530
in the World Economy tonight.

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:16.290
I will focus on the policy aspects,

00:13:16.290 --> 00:13:18.950
but also focus on the economic argument.

00:13:18.950 --> 00:13:22.290
And I want to start this by saying that

00:13:22.290 --> 00:13:25.270
I myself have not spent most of my life

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:28.410
studying women in the global economy.

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:30.610
I got to this issue personally,

00:13:30.610 --> 00:13:32.860
and I got fascinated by
it, maybe I developed

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:36.183
a little passion for
it, relatively recently.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:39.160
The first thing I had passion for

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:41.230
as a student was economics.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:43.850
And when I studied economics,

00:13:43.850 --> 00:13:47.630
I went to Smith College,
and I did not realize,

00:13:47.630 --> 00:13:50.060
because I was at an all women's school,

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:53.110
that economics was a male discipline.

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:55.050
So I liked economics.

00:13:55.050 --> 00:13:57.210
Most of my professors were actually,

00:13:57.210 --> 00:13:59.240
at that point, male professors,

00:13:59.240 --> 00:14:02.570
but I thought the
discipline was fantastic.

00:14:02.570 --> 00:14:05.550
And I tend therefore to think about

00:14:05.550 --> 00:14:08.680
problems that interest
me are economic problems.

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:11.870
I went to MIT, and at MIT I studied

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:13.770
International Economic Development,

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:16.180
in comparative political economy,

00:14:16.180 --> 00:14:18.990
how do societies organize themselves

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:21.540
to be competitive, to be prosperous,

00:14:21.540 --> 00:14:26.404
to promote rapid growth
in output per person,

00:14:26.404 --> 00:14:30.410
to have great productivity,
what do societies do?

00:14:30.410 --> 00:14:33.990
So one of the things that
I discovered increasingly

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:37.630
was that, how societies treat women,

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:41.010
their gender, what I'm gonna
call all my gender parity,

00:14:41.010 --> 00:14:45.810
the extent to which men and
women are treated equally

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:47.150
in a variety of areas.

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:51.050
That gender parity actually
does have an effect

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:53.620
on an economy's economic performance.

00:14:53.620 --> 00:14:57.760
And it's an effect which
actually in the past 20 years

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:01.460
has really been demonstrated
in study after study.

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:04.080
So whereas we might've
thought that before,

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:07.360
we might've just had an
intuition that was true,

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:09.760
we have a very dramatic
amount of evidence now

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:13.080
coming from economists,
coming from psychologists,

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:14.640
coming from political scientists,

00:15:14.640 --> 00:15:17.170
coming from countries all over the world,

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:21.800
that countries that have
greater degrees of gender parity

00:15:22.850 --> 00:15:26.600
also have a superior economic performance

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:27.780
in a variety of ways.

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:29.953
So I'm gonna talk about that tonight.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:35.240
I got first interested in this question

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:37.480
because I was, as I said,

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:39.130
I was always interested in economics,

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:41.920
always interested in how societies perform

00:15:41.920 --> 00:15:44.053
comparatively, competitively.

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:47.330
But I was the dean of two
business schools also.

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:50.240
The business school here,
right across the street.

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:52.350
A great business school, fantastic,

00:15:52.350 --> 00:15:55.040
London Business School also
a wonderful business school.

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:57.670
One if more international
in makeup than the other,

00:15:57.670 --> 00:16:00.060
but they're actually at
the top of their game.

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:03.130
And what I discovered,
and I should've known this

00:16:03.130 --> 00:16:04.630
but I discovered it,

00:16:04.630 --> 00:16:07.920
was that business schools
were one of the few

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:12.920
higher education areas
where women were not yet

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:18.170
at the 50% or parity level
in terms of enrollment.

00:16:18.170 --> 00:16:19.980
Women weren't going to business school

00:16:19.980 --> 00:16:22.050
to the same extent as men were.

00:16:22.050 --> 00:16:23.190
If they went to business school,

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:25.000
they were not staying in business school.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.560
If they graduated from business school,

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:27.680
they were not staying in business.

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:30.260
So this was like, I noticed this.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:32.710
And I tried to begin to understand,

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:35.980
since I was a female dean
of two business schools,

00:16:35.980 --> 00:16:40.980
what business schools might
do to encourage more women.

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:43.300
In the process of thinking about that,

00:16:43.300 --> 00:16:45.590
there were others around
the world thinking about

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:48.520
how to, they were looking at
this business case for women,

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:50.030
the economic case for women,

00:16:50.030 --> 00:16:52.340
the economic case for gender parity,

00:16:52.340 --> 00:16:54.900
I was approached by something called

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:56.160
the World Economic Forum.

00:16:56.160 --> 00:16:58.560
So the World Economic
Forum is a non-profit,

00:16:58.560 --> 00:17:01.630
it's very influential,
it grew out of actually

00:17:01.630 --> 00:17:06.560
an academic institution in
Switzerland 45 years ago.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.410
It has become very
influential around the world.

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:12.240
It brings together great
leaders from around the world,

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:13.710
both business and political leaders,

00:17:13.710 --> 00:17:16.320
to talk about pressing economic issues,

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:19.300
and to think about what are the factors

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:22.920
that lead to an economy's success.

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:25.150
So the World Economic Forum approached me

00:17:25.150 --> 00:17:26.530
while I was thinking about

00:17:26.530 --> 00:17:28.900
why aren't there more
women in business schools,

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:33.900
and said, "We want to put
together a rigorous analysis of

00:17:35.467 --> 00:17:39.347
"how countries are doing on gender parity

00:17:39.347 --> 00:17:41.227
"in a number of dimensions.

00:17:41.227 --> 00:17:45.677
"And then we want to see
how a country's performance

00:17:45.677 --> 00:17:49.040
"on gender parity affects
its economic performance."

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:50.910
That was their mission.

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:53.610
And they asked if I would
be interested in doing this,

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:54.730
and I said, absolutely.

00:17:54.730 --> 00:17:57.020
Because I had been thinking about it.

00:17:57.020 --> 00:18:02.020
So we got some very
good help at the Forum.

00:18:02.320 --> 00:18:05.830
We got a couple of really
good data economists.

00:18:05.830 --> 00:18:09.010
I'm more of an economist who sort of does

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:10.730
case studies, and country studies,

00:18:10.730 --> 00:18:13.400
so we've got some very good,
rigorous data economists.

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:16.420
And we put together a report which has

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:21.420
come to be called the
Global Gender Gap Report.

00:18:21.780 --> 00:18:24.700
Now before I start with the numbers,

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:27.920
I wanna tell just a personal anecdote

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:31.370
about my first engagement
with the World Economic Forum,

00:18:31.370 --> 00:18:36.370
'cause it predated when they
came to me in 2003 and '04

00:18:37.440 --> 00:18:39.230
and said, "Will you work on this issue?".

00:18:39.230 --> 00:18:41.720
I had gone to the World Economic Forum

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:44.450
as a member of the US government

00:18:45.310 --> 00:18:47.640
working for Bill Clinton,

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:49.713
and my spouse had come along.

00:18:50.690 --> 00:18:54.193
And this was the mid 1990s.

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:59.770
So at that point there were very few men

00:19:00.670 --> 00:19:03.544
who were spouses at the
World Economic Forum.

00:19:03.544 --> 00:19:04.377
(light audience laughter)

00:19:04.377 --> 00:19:05.370
There were a whole bunch of women

00:19:05.370 --> 00:19:07.560
who were spouses at the
World Economic Forum,

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:09.540
and very few men.

00:19:09.540 --> 00:19:11.830
So we arrived, my husband and I,

00:19:13.420 --> 00:19:15.993
and he was offered a flowered bag,

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:19.457
and I was offered a black briefcase.

00:19:19.457 --> 00:19:20.510
(audience laughter)

00:19:20.510 --> 00:19:24.290
He was offered a sleigh ride through town,

00:19:24.290 --> 00:19:27.500
and I was offered a panel to discuss

00:19:27.500 --> 00:19:29.930
global economic activity.

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:32.120
Back in the mid 1990s,

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:34.840
spouses were not invited to go to

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:37.680
the major sessions of
the World Economic Forum.

00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:39.220
By the way, there's at least one person

00:19:39.220 --> 00:19:41.560
in the audience who knows
my husband pretty well,

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:44.350
and she can guess, he was not pleased.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:45.870
(audience laughter)

00:19:45.870 --> 00:19:48.470
In fact, he has refused ever to go back

00:19:48.470 --> 00:19:50.150
to the World Economic Forum with me,

00:19:50.150 --> 00:19:52.620
even though I tell him on a regular basis,

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:55.590
look, no sleigh rides, no flowered bags,

00:19:55.590 --> 00:19:57.720
you can go to whatever event you want to,

00:19:57.720 --> 00:19:58.680
it's all right, dear.

00:19:58.680 --> 00:19:59.923
No, no, he's not coming.

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:05.440
So this is just an anecdote
about changing style,

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:09.370
because now the World Economic Forum,

00:20:09.370 --> 00:20:12.080
although in itself has
not reached gender parity,

00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:16.040
absolutely not, so 20% of
its participants are women,

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:18.760
but what I will say is
you have some of the

00:20:18.760 --> 00:20:20.880
major women leaders
around the world there.

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:22.960
You have major female CEOs there,

00:20:22.960 --> 00:20:24.940
you have whole panels talking about

00:20:24.940 --> 00:20:28.470
what companies can do to
promote greater gender parity,

00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:31.350
what countries can do to
promote greater gender parity.

00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:34.320
So its gone from a non-issue

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:37.190
to an absolutely central
issue of the Forum.

00:20:37.190 --> 00:20:39.977
And that's because, what
I'm gonna show you now

00:20:39.977 --> 00:20:41.760
are some of the results,

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.660
what the evidence shows very clearly

00:20:44.660 --> 00:20:48.170
is that countries that
develop greater gender parity

00:20:48.170 --> 00:20:50.950
over time in a variety of measures,

00:20:50.950 --> 00:20:55.040
actually do end up having
superior economic performance,

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:56.160
and we can talk about why.

00:20:56.160 --> 00:21:00.053
So let me just tell you
a little bit about this,

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.770
what the gender gap is trying to measure.

00:21:04.770 --> 00:21:06.260
Now I'm gonna say you can go to the

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:08.470
World Economic Forum website.

00:21:08.470 --> 00:21:11.980
The reports there, it's
become the second most

00:21:11.980 --> 00:21:14.210
important report of the
World Economic Forum

00:21:14.210 --> 00:21:15.210
all around the world,

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:18.270
so people do at least look at it.

00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:19.550
It is a very good report,

00:21:19.550 --> 00:21:21.460
but it's pretty tedious reading.

00:21:21.460 --> 00:21:23.830
You have to go in and
sort of each country,

00:21:23.830 --> 00:21:25.820
you look at a whole bunch of measures.

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:27.690
So I'm gonna try to summarize for you

00:21:27.690 --> 00:21:30.080
what the results are.

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:35.080
So we tried to measure gender parity

00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:38.100
on a variety of dimensions that we thought

00:21:38.100 --> 00:21:41.040
were relevant to economic performance.

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:45.020
Obviously education is relevant
to economic performance.

00:21:45.020 --> 00:21:47.930
So a country that, if you think about

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:50.540
the workforce as being half female,

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:54.400
you wanna educate the workforce
literate to illiteracy,

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:57.440
primary, secondary, tertiary,
all the way through,

00:21:57.440 --> 00:22:01.200
you want to basically
achieve gender parity

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:04.510
in educational opportunity,
and educational attainment.

00:22:04.510 --> 00:22:06.710
So that was an obvious one.

00:22:06.710 --> 00:22:09.600
Health and survival, obvious.

00:22:09.600 --> 00:22:13.400
A country's performance
on the health and survival

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:15.650
of men and women, and
whether there are any

00:22:15.650 --> 00:22:18.560
gender issues there is important.

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:20.800
Economic participation and opportunity.

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:23.270
So this is really, we look
at lots of things here.

00:22:23.270 --> 00:22:25.450
We look at what economists call

00:22:25.450 --> 00:22:28.040
labor force participation rates,

00:22:28.040 --> 00:22:32.147
to what extent is the female population

00:22:33.840 --> 00:22:37.890
of working age working,
labor force participation.

00:22:37.890 --> 00:22:39.030
But we don't just measure that,

00:22:39.030 --> 00:22:41.420
we measure pay gaps, gender gaps,

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:44.330
female, male differences in earnings.

00:22:44.330 --> 00:22:46.580
And we measure opportunity gaps,

00:22:46.580 --> 00:22:49.590
which we kind of look at
through attainment levels,

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:51.460
and you'll see some of that later.

00:22:51.460 --> 00:22:53.853
And then political empowerment,

00:22:55.090 --> 00:22:59.710
because policies about the economy,

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:03.400
policies about education,
policies about health

00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:06.820
are going to be affected
by the gender parity,

00:23:06.820 --> 00:23:10.480
or lack thereof, in
political representation.

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:12.530
So these are the areas.

00:23:12.530 --> 00:23:15.300
We have 142 countries.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:18.270
We have 14 variables, we rate them.

00:23:18.270 --> 00:23:21.110
We now have nine years of data.

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:23.810
So you can sort of compare
countries over time

00:23:23.810 --> 00:23:25.870
in terms of are they improving,

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:27.690
are they improving on one dimension

00:23:27.690 --> 00:23:29.120
but declining on another.

00:23:29.120 --> 00:23:32.240
So this is what we're attempting to study.

00:23:32.240 --> 00:23:33.780
And we believe that four of these,

00:23:33.780 --> 00:23:35.560
these four areas are the major ones

00:23:35.560 --> 00:23:40.260
for understanding a society's
approach to gender parity,

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:43.340
and we believe it's very important
for economic performance.

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:45.460
So that's the first thing.

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:48.420
Okay, this is a little
graphic which kind of says

00:23:49.550 --> 00:23:50.690
how the world is doing.

00:23:50.690 --> 00:23:55.690
So each country gets measured,

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:58.740
but we also do a weighted
average of all countries

00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:01.800
to sort of say how's the
world on average doing

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:05.280
in gender parity in education,
gender parity in health,

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:08.020
in economic opportunity,
and political empowerment.

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:11.720
And we use weighting measures.

00:24:11.720 --> 00:24:14.520
And what you can see right
here is that actually

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:18.880
the world today has made a
tremendous amount of progress

00:24:19.750 --> 00:24:22.160
in eliminating gender disparities

00:24:22.160 --> 00:24:25.500
in health, and in education.

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:30.250
It has eliminated, not eliminated,

00:24:30.250 --> 00:24:33.110
it's reduced disparities in

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:35.450
economic participation and opportunity,

00:24:35.450 --> 00:24:37.040
but there's a lot left to do.

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:39.100
So you might read that as

00:24:39.100 --> 00:24:41.873
the world has eliminated 60% of the gap.

00:24:43.430 --> 00:24:46.990
And then in political empowerment,

00:24:46.990 --> 00:24:48.740
we have a long way to go.

00:24:48.740 --> 00:24:51.550
Around the world,
there's a long way to go.

00:24:51.550 --> 00:24:53.880
Now I wanna say something about,

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:56.900
I wanna warn you about these numbers

00:24:56.900 --> 00:24:59.440
before I show some countries.

00:24:59.440 --> 00:25:02.350
Just because a country
is doing pretty well

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:06.120
in terms of parity, doesn't mean that

00:25:06.120 --> 00:25:10.320
the level of education
or health is that high.

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:11.810
So we have a whole bunch of countries.

00:25:11.810 --> 00:25:13.530
Some are very developed.

00:25:13.530 --> 00:25:16.180
And they have a high
degree of gender parity.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:18.860
That means they're getting
high levels of education,

00:25:18.860 --> 00:25:19.920
high levels of health,

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:23.350
and not much gender
difference in those areas.

00:25:23.350 --> 00:25:25.230
You have some very poor countries

00:25:25.230 --> 00:25:28.000
who actually are doing
pretty well in gender parity,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:29.840
but they're poor, they're poor.

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:32.800
So their degree of tertiary education

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:35.550
for both men and women might be low,

00:25:35.550 --> 00:25:40.550
or their degree of health
outcomes might be low

00:25:40.760 --> 00:25:42.640
for both men and women.

00:25:42.640 --> 00:25:46.127
So I just wanna make sure
that one understands that

00:25:46.127 --> 00:25:49.040
to have a country score,

00:25:49.040 --> 00:25:51.220
a country score of one on something

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:53.600
means complete gender parity.

00:25:53.600 --> 00:25:54.433
Okay?

00:25:55.290 --> 00:25:57.830
Very few countries get
that on almost anything,

00:25:57.830 --> 00:26:01.510
so now we will go to the next slide.

00:26:01.510 --> 00:26:02.623
Who's in the lead?

00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:06.690
This is a graph which just shows averages,

00:26:06.690 --> 00:26:08.840
so those little lines are averages.

00:26:08.840 --> 00:26:11.960
Not to be, you would not
be surprised that we,

00:26:11.960 --> 00:26:14.520
when you look at these
countries, 142 countries,

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:16.770
there's gonna be a regional effect.

00:26:16.770 --> 00:26:20.750
So the highest average
gender parity measures

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:24.240
are in North America, the US and Canada,

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:26.930
however if you go down to
Europe and Central Asia,

00:26:26.930 --> 00:26:30.300
Europe has actually, those ones
way on the the right there,

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:33.220
they are basically the
best performers in the lot,

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:34.960
and I'm gonna talk about them in a minute.

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:37.000
There is a group of
European countries who,

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.270
on all dimensions,
outperform everybody else.

00:26:40.270 --> 00:26:44.030
And some of you can probably
guess which ones those are.

00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:45.390
They're on the right.

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:47.870
If you go down to the Middle
East and North Africa,

00:26:47.870 --> 00:26:50.360
you'll see the average is the lowest,

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:53.673
and you have some very
extreme outliers there.

00:26:54.600 --> 00:26:59.600
This shows, and I'll get to
a table, or a slide later,

00:26:59.710 --> 00:27:04.060
when you think about reasons
for gender disparities,

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:07.390
clearly one of them is
going to be cultural.

00:27:07.390 --> 00:27:11.010
And I think you see
both a development level

00:27:11.010 --> 00:27:12.630
and a cultural level showing up

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:15.360
in some of these regional differences.

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:18.770
Let me just, since countries
like to see where they are,

00:27:18.770 --> 00:27:20.360
one of the fascinating things about

00:27:20.360 --> 00:27:23.270
if you ever create an index of everything,

00:27:23.270 --> 00:27:26.630
excuse me, create an index
of anything by country,

00:27:26.630 --> 00:27:28.790
countries start to compete on it.

00:27:28.790 --> 00:27:33.790
So actually, this report
has become widely read.

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:36.540
In part because country leaders,

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:40.650
business leaders in a
country, NGOs in a country,

00:27:40.650 --> 00:27:43.760
educational institutions, look
at how the country's doing,

00:27:43.760 --> 00:27:44.980
and then they try to figure out

00:27:44.980 --> 00:27:47.200
what can they do to get better.

00:27:47.200 --> 00:27:50.940
So this has the top 20 over here.

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:52.950
You'll see the United States is number 20.

00:27:52.950 --> 00:27:55.410
And then it has some of the
other countries over there

00:27:55.410 --> 00:27:59.810
going to the bottom,
Yemen 142, Pakistan 141,

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:02.070
and Saudi Arabia 130.

00:28:02.070 --> 00:28:05.763
And by the way, Saudi Arabia
has improved its gender gap,

00:28:06.660 --> 00:28:10.603
it's reduced its gender gap
in the last couple of years.

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:12.820
It's moving in the right direction,

00:28:12.820 --> 00:28:16.530
but it's still as a ranking phenomenon,

00:28:16.530 --> 00:28:19.730
one of the least performing countries.

00:28:19.730 --> 00:28:22.823
So let's talk a little bit
about who's in the lead.

00:28:24.340 --> 00:28:29.240
So you'll see those top
five countries there,

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:31.360
they're the Nordic countries.

00:28:31.360 --> 00:28:32.460
For some of you in this room,

00:28:32.460 --> 00:28:35.850
that would not be a surprise,
you would predict that.

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:38.120
That actually suggests a combination

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:41.820
of culture and policy
are very important here,

00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:44.740
the policy is reflecting the culture.

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:49.740
And so when you have things
like compulsory paternity leave,

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:52.240
not just maternity leave,
but paternity leave,

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:55.150
so you don't have any
scapegoating of men and women,

00:28:55.150 --> 00:28:57.370
both parents have to take leave

00:28:57.370 --> 00:28:59.490
to take care of the children.

00:28:59.490 --> 00:29:03.020
When you have highly subsidized childcare

00:29:03.020 --> 00:29:04.880
that lasts a very long time,

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:08.270
when you have support
for part-time workers

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:10.870
at full-time salaries
so that people have time

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:11.990
to take care of their children,

00:29:11.990 --> 00:29:13.350
for both men and women.

00:29:13.350 --> 00:29:18.060
Those are reflections of
a set of social norms,

00:29:18.060 --> 00:29:20.840
which actually end up in policy

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:24.930
that actually does have an
effect on gender parity.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:26.693
If you go to the US for a minute,

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:30.940
the US, not a bad performer.

00:29:30.940 --> 00:29:32.740
This number says we've eliminated

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:35.770
75% of our aggregate gender gap.

00:29:35.770 --> 00:29:39.310
Where the US is weakest is politics.

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:41.150
We do not do well here.

00:29:41.150 --> 00:29:45.830
We're like, the way we measure politics,

00:29:45.830 --> 00:29:47.940
we've only eliminated 20% of the gap.

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:51.080
I think we're number 60
out of 142 countries.

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:52.810
We have a lot of room to go

00:29:52.810 --> 00:29:55.420
in politics in the United States.

00:29:55.420 --> 00:29:58.610
We measure politics here
in parliamentary seats,

00:29:58.610 --> 00:30:02.303
ministerial positions, and head of state.

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:06.680
You might say, now this
is just for those of you

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.720
who think about the challenges

00:30:08.720 --> 00:30:11.210
of doing something like this with data.

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:16.210
An ideal thing would be to
include mayors, or city council.

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:19.950
The problem is, you can't
get numbers like that

00:30:19.950 --> 00:30:21.520
for the 142 countries.

00:30:21.520 --> 00:30:23.150
You can't get it from
many countries at all,

00:30:23.150 --> 00:30:25.730
so if you're trying to
do this comparatively,

00:30:25.730 --> 00:30:28.400
you have to chose data, statistics,

00:30:28.400 --> 00:30:31.460
measures that are common across countries.

00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:33.530
And that's how we end up with ministers,

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:36.360
parliamentarians and heads of state.

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:38.480
If we managed to have a head of state

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:41.520
as a woman in the next few years,

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:43.800
this would fundamentally
change our position.

00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:46.910
But that's, I'm not
saying anything political.

00:30:46.910 --> 00:30:50.042
That's a purely statistical
observation, all right.

00:30:50.042 --> 00:30:50.875
(audience laughter)

00:30:50.875 --> 00:30:52.050
Purely statistical.

00:30:52.050 --> 00:30:53.500
Dynamics of the gender gaps.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:56.110
So we've done this for
nine years, any progress?

00:30:56.110 --> 00:30:58.220
Not a whole lot.

00:30:58.220 --> 00:31:00.720
There's stuff going on in pol--

00:31:00.720 --> 00:31:03.270
First of all, this shows
very clearly, again,

00:31:03.270 --> 00:31:07.230
that the biggest gaps around
the world are in politics.

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:10.430
The most reduced gaps are
in education and health,

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:12.810
and the economic participation
and opportunities

00:31:12.810 --> 00:31:14.910
are kind of in the middle there.

00:31:14.910 --> 00:31:16.070
We have made some progress

00:31:16.070 --> 00:31:19.040
around the world in political empowerment.

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:22.180
The progress is pretty slow.

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:24.980
You can barely see, you
can see a little progress

00:31:24.980 --> 00:31:29.300
in the economic participation
and opportunity line.

00:31:29.300 --> 00:31:31.700
The last time the report came out,

00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:34.160
my colleagues at the World Economic Forum

00:31:34.160 --> 00:31:36.080
used the rate of progress

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:38.310
in economic participation and opportunity,

00:31:38.310 --> 00:31:40.640
and concluded if the world continues

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:43.130
at the progress of the last nine years,

00:31:43.130 --> 00:31:46.880
it'll take 81 years to
close the gender gap

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:49.090
in economic participation and opportunity.

00:31:49.090 --> 00:31:50.473
So I think the world's
gonna be better than that.

00:31:50.473 --> 00:31:52.370
I don't think it's gonna take 81 years,

00:31:52.370 --> 00:31:55.150
but that's what we found out.

00:31:55.150 --> 00:31:56.740
So.

00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:58.020
Now next.

00:31:58.020 --> 00:31:58.853
Okay.

00:31:58.853 --> 00:32:02.010
So now, this is what
the World Economic Forum

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:03.883
when they started to do this,

00:32:05.650 --> 00:32:09.770
this is a question they were
interested in answering.

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:11.030
Remember, the World Economic Forum

00:32:11.030 --> 00:32:16.030
made its reputation by ranking countries

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:18.943
on their competitiveness
in the global economy.

00:32:18.943 --> 00:32:22.510
It's something called the
Global Competitiveness Index.

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:24.020
And that's how they made their reputation.

00:32:24.020 --> 00:32:26.360
When I was back there with
my husband and flowered bags,

00:32:26.360 --> 00:32:28.600
that's the index they had.

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:32.520
And they had a whole host
of things they measured

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:34.470
that they thought might be correlated

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:38.340
with competitiveness,
national competitiveness.

00:32:38.340 --> 00:32:42.653
Things like the rule of law, open trading,

00:32:45.250 --> 00:32:49.010
regulation, education.

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:51.390
Gender, not there.

00:32:51.390 --> 00:32:52.223
Not there.

00:32:52.223 --> 00:32:54.690
Remember, it was the mid
1990s, gender wasn't there.

00:32:54.690 --> 00:32:59.690
So the challenge for us was to say

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:02.510
would gender parity show up

00:33:02.510 --> 00:33:05.440
as something that we
think it's related to,

00:33:05.440 --> 00:33:07.810
global competitiveness,
but does it show up?

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:11.150
So this suggests that yes, there
is a positive relationship,

00:33:11.150 --> 00:33:12.610
it's statistically significant,

00:33:12.610 --> 00:33:15.670
between how a country performs on its

00:33:15.670 --> 00:33:18.900
global gender gap index, and
its global competitiveness.

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:21.830
So moving towards gender parity

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:27.670
is associated with a
more competitive outcome.

00:33:27.670 --> 00:33:31.430
And so the whole reason
for doing the study

00:33:31.430 --> 00:33:33.940
in the first place,
once we had the numbers

00:33:33.940 --> 00:33:36.820
we could say okay, that seems to be

00:33:36.820 --> 00:33:39.480
a relationship that makes sense.

00:33:39.480 --> 00:33:41.350
And then there's another one you can do,

00:33:41.350 --> 00:33:44.350
but it's a little bit the same thing.

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:46.750
Global competitiveness is linked to

00:33:46.750 --> 00:33:50.360
global GDP per capita, and GDP per capita

00:33:50.360 --> 00:33:53.950
is the economist's favorite
measure of prosperity,

00:33:53.950 --> 00:33:57.660
so you measure a country's
prosperity by GDP per capita.

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:00.680
And this says, yes, there
is a relationship between

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:03.740
the global gender gap
index and GDP per capita.

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:07.050
So those were things that we
had anticipated finding out,

00:34:07.050 --> 00:34:09.280
and we did find them.

00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:10.680
So.

00:34:10.680 --> 00:34:12.050
Now I'm gonna,

00:34:12.050 --> 00:34:13.570
maybe I shouldn't put this one up yet.

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:15.670
There's a lot more that I now wanna say,

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:20.230
moving from the World
Economic Forum itself

00:34:20.230 --> 00:34:22.750
to actually other work that's been done

00:34:22.750 --> 00:34:27.100
during this whole period, on women,

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:29.600
gender parity, and economic performance.

00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:32.850
So the World Economic Forum is one study,

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:35.530
one set of measures that
looks at this relationship.

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:36.730
I mentioned at the beginning,

00:34:36.730 --> 00:34:38.920
there's been a lot of
work going on on this,

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:41.350
the International Monetary
Fund is working on it,

00:34:41.350 --> 00:34:43.320
the World Bank is working on it,

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:45.450
development economists have worked on it.

00:34:45.450 --> 00:34:49.600
And basically what they are working on,

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:54.000
is how does a greater gender parity

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.430
affect economic performance, and why?

00:34:56.430 --> 00:34:59.120
How does it affect it, and why?

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:02.200
Now to some extent, this is intuitive,

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:03.810
it's absolutely intuitive.

00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:08.810
If half of the global
labor force was women,

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:13.440
and if women are becoming
as educated as men,

00:35:13.440 --> 00:35:16.130
and we saw that in
terms of the gender gaps

00:35:16.130 --> 00:35:20.240
in education really
disappearing around the world,

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:23.940
then clearly, if you
believe that human talent

00:35:24.970 --> 00:35:28.210
has an effect on economic performance,

00:35:28.210 --> 00:35:30.920
then what you want to do is say that

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:34.260
greater gender parity
and economic opportunity

00:35:34.260 --> 00:35:39.200
and participation will mean
greater mobilization of talent,

00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:42.200
and that will lead to
superior economic performance.

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:46.540
It's a very simple intuitive relationship.

00:35:46.540 --> 00:35:48.690
And I think that's really what

00:35:48.690 --> 00:35:53.640
a lot of the research is now focused on.

00:35:53.640 --> 00:35:55.883
Now if you think about it that way,

00:35:57.630 --> 00:36:01.230
how does one look at measurements

00:36:01.230 --> 00:36:06.150
of mobilizing gender talent.

00:36:06.150 --> 00:36:08.240
One simple way is what I mentioned before,

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:11.163
labor force participation rates.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:13.470
The International Monetary Fund

00:36:13.470 --> 00:36:17.130
is headed by a very outstanding
woman, Christine Lagarde,

00:36:17.130 --> 00:36:19.630
and when she goes around the
world talking to countries

00:36:19.630 --> 00:36:24.480
and giving them advice
about how to promote

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:26.510
their future economic prosperity,

00:36:26.510 --> 00:36:28.920
this is one of the
statistics she focuses on.

00:36:28.920 --> 00:36:33.290
Labor force participation rate for women,

00:36:33.290 --> 00:36:35.860
and if you can get that
labor force participation

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:39.880
rate for women up to
closer to that for men,

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:42.760
there will be faster economic growth.

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:44.500
So the OECD, for example,

00:36:44.500 --> 00:36:48.800
has estimated that if
there was gender parity

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:51.580
in labor force participation rates between

00:36:51.580 --> 00:36:55.040
men and women in the developed economies,

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:59.720
that would lead to an
increase by about 12%

00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:02.903
of GDP per capita over a 20 year basis.

00:37:02.903 --> 00:37:04.870
That's a big number.

00:37:04.870 --> 00:37:07.130
You know, people sit
around all around the world

00:37:07.130 --> 00:37:08.070
trying to figure out what to do

00:37:08.070 --> 00:37:09.720
to promote economic growth,

00:37:09.720 --> 00:37:11.330
that number is a big number.

00:37:11.330 --> 00:37:13.040
So if you can figure out a way

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:15.860
to mobilize women into the workforce,

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:18.030
that is gonna be a big movement towards

00:37:18.030 --> 00:37:20.460
superior economic performance.

00:37:20.460 --> 00:37:23.590
But it's not just mobilizing
women in the workforce.

00:37:23.590 --> 00:37:26.610
The other things you
have to worry about are

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:28.950
around the world, in the US,

00:37:28.950 --> 00:37:31.150
in every country to some extent,

00:37:31.150 --> 00:37:34.340
even in the Nordic countries,

00:37:34.340 --> 00:37:37.000
women tend to be over represented

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:41.130
in relatively low productivity,

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:45.500
part-time, low pay, with
low advancement opportunity

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:47.850
sectors of the economy.

00:37:47.850 --> 00:37:49.580
They're over represented there,

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:53.010
and they're under represented in high pay,

00:37:53.010 --> 00:37:56.600
high productivity, high
opportunity sectors.

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:58.130
So if you actually are interested

00:37:58.130 --> 00:37:59.780
in mobilizing female talent,

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:02.870
it's not just getting them to participate

00:38:02.870 --> 00:38:04.960
in the workforce as much as men,

00:38:04.960 --> 00:38:07.790
but to have them have the opportunities

00:38:07.790 --> 00:38:11.510
in these high productivity,
high performance,

00:38:11.510 --> 00:38:14.220
high pay, high opportunity careers.

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:18.050
So looking at that suggests one looks at

00:38:18.050 --> 00:38:20.980
not just the labor force
participation rates,

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:23.200
but the wage gaps, or the wage rates,

00:38:23.200 --> 00:38:25.193
or the productivity differences.

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:31.070
And what you see there is just
like all around the world,

00:38:31.070 --> 00:38:34.370
the labor force
participation rates of women

00:38:34.370 --> 00:38:36.383
tend to be lower than men.

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:40.350
There is a persistent wage gap.

00:38:40.350 --> 00:38:43.890
Now the wage gap varies by country.

00:38:43.890 --> 00:38:45.480
It varies by sector.

00:38:45.480 --> 00:38:48.770
But you would still say
that it's persistent,

00:38:48.770 --> 00:38:52.410
it's measurable, and it's significant.

00:38:52.410 --> 00:38:54.850
It's not a trivial number.

00:38:54.850 --> 00:38:56.470
And part of that gap of course,

00:38:56.470 --> 00:38:59.950
is that women are caught more

00:38:59.950 --> 00:39:02.620
in these low productivity, low pay jobs.

00:39:02.620 --> 00:39:06.710
But even if you hold constant sector,

00:39:06.710 --> 00:39:09.360
even if you hold constant jobs,

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:10.990
then you still see the wage gap.

00:39:10.990 --> 00:39:15.000
So for example, in the US, female earnings

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:18.130
remain lower than men's
for similar skill levels

00:39:18.130 --> 00:39:20.190
in nearly all occupations.

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:21.850
That's in the US.

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:25.370
Including occupations that
are predominantly held by men,

00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:27.830
and occupations that are
predominantly held by women.

00:39:27.830 --> 00:39:31.300
Even in occupations
predominantly held by women,

00:39:31.300 --> 00:39:32.970
there is a wage gap.

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:35.950
And that's for women of
same educational levels.

00:39:35.950 --> 00:39:38.880
So that's important.

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:40.320
Another thing that's important,

00:39:40.320 --> 00:39:42.900
certainly relevant to
this audience I would say,

00:39:42.900 --> 00:39:45.370
is the wage gap tends to start small

00:39:45.370 --> 00:39:47.810
for young women entering the labor force,

00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:49.230
certainly in developed countries.

00:39:49.230 --> 00:39:51.380
That would be true in the US.

00:39:51.380 --> 00:39:53.760
Small wage gap at the beginning

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:56.150
gets bigger over time.

00:39:56.150 --> 00:39:58.730
Increases with child birth.

00:39:58.730 --> 00:40:00.360
But here's a surprise,

00:40:00.360 --> 00:40:03.710
is larger among top earners

00:40:03.710 --> 00:40:07.810
and those with high levels
of educational attainment.

00:40:07.810 --> 00:40:08.933
It gets larger.

00:40:09.860 --> 00:40:13.380
And that, of course, is partly because

00:40:13.380 --> 00:40:16.780
of what has been commonly
called opting out,

00:40:16.780 --> 00:40:21.780
or motherhood, or taking care
of family responsibilities.

00:40:22.050 --> 00:40:25.040
You know there was
just, and I urge you all

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:27.980
to take a look at it,
it's really remarkable.

00:40:27.980 --> 00:40:31.030
My son just got married three weeks ago.

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:34.730
Harvard Business School does a big survey

00:40:34.730 --> 00:40:39.730
of male and female graduates
over the past 40 years.

00:40:41.940 --> 00:40:43.920
So they have some graduates

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:46.120
who are baby boomers like myself,

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:49.810
they have some millennials,
who are just 30 years old.

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:51.450
They asked the men and the women

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:56.510
what they expected in terms of

00:40:56.510 --> 00:41:00.300
did they think their
career would be equally

00:41:00.300 --> 00:41:04.050
as important as their
partners, or less important,

00:41:04.050 --> 00:41:06.850
and did they think
childcare responsibilities

00:41:06.850 --> 00:41:09.343
would be equally shared,
or unequally shared.

00:41:10.870 --> 00:41:14.410
Women thought they were equally important,

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:17.380
and responsibilities
would be equally shared.

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:18.665
Men did not.

00:41:18.665 --> 00:41:19.498
(audient laughter)

00:41:19.498 --> 00:41:23.950
These are expectations of Harvard
Business School graduates.

00:41:23.950 --> 00:41:27.790
Right, so this is now, this is today.

00:41:27.790 --> 00:41:29.660
This is right now.

00:41:29.660 --> 00:41:33.420
So you think about how the pressures on,

00:41:33.420 --> 00:41:34.520
when you see these numbers,

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:38.950
okay, the wage gap starts out not there,

00:41:38.950 --> 00:41:40.510
and then develops over time,

00:41:40.510 --> 00:41:42.340
and it develops over time with children,

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:45.620
and people opting out, and
all the responsibilities

00:41:45.620 --> 00:41:47.738
that Esther said you have to juggle,

00:41:47.738 --> 00:41:50.500
you still have to juggle.

00:41:50.500 --> 00:41:54.740
And societies that have made it easier,

00:41:54.740 --> 00:41:56.430
that's the Nordic countries,

00:41:56.430 --> 00:41:59.650
tend to have over time,
better performance here

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:04.200
because they're taking some of
these family balancing issues

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:08.090
and they are working to make them easier.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:10.740
So it's just an important point

00:42:10.740 --> 00:42:15.740
about the opting out
pressures of family on women,

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:19.020
and the fact that the OECD says

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:23.530
their estimate is the wage penalty,

00:42:23.530 --> 00:42:25.863
terrible thing to say, per child,

00:42:25.863 --> 00:42:27.830
7% of your earnings.

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:28.663
Okay.

00:42:28.663 --> 00:42:30.810
This is among developed countries.

00:42:30.810 --> 00:42:33.793
So this is some of the issues.

00:42:36.210 --> 00:42:38.570
Now, I wanna go from that however,

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:40.980
to make two important observations.

00:42:40.980 --> 00:42:45.980
Number one, the opting out
phenomenon is real, and costly,

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:49.740
but it does not say, in any way,

00:42:49.740 --> 00:42:52.670
that women are less ambitious than men.

00:42:52.670 --> 00:42:55.840
So again, in developed countries
there are lots of surveys,

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:58.312
including the Harvard survey
that I just talked about,

00:42:58.312 --> 00:43:01.960
aspirationally speaking,
women want the same thing.

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:04.240
They want the same thing on average.

00:43:04.240 --> 00:43:05.980
It's just harder for them to achieve.

00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:08.690
So this is not about
aspiration and ambition,

00:43:08.690 --> 00:43:11.493
this is about how complicated
it is to achieve that.

00:43:13.420 --> 00:43:16.280
And the next thing is to say that

00:43:18.870 --> 00:43:21.550
