00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:15.560
in developed countries, in companies,

00:47:15.560 --> 00:47:19.600
and in policy, to think
about what we can do

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:22.050
to improve the flow
through in the pipeline.

00:47:22.050 --> 00:47:25.920
Because after all, if
women are getting educated

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:28.430
to this very high level,

00:47:28.430 --> 00:47:30.320
and we're losing them in the pipeline,

00:47:30.320 --> 00:47:32.990
and some of that can be improved by better

00:47:32.990 --> 00:47:37.990
workplace training, better
workplace evaluation of talent,

00:47:38.860 --> 00:47:39.790
then we should do that.

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:41.580
That's better for the company,

00:47:41.580 --> 00:47:43.410
it's better for the individual,

00:47:43.410 --> 00:47:45.310
it's better for the country.

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:49.440
So that's something
that I think has become

00:47:49.440 --> 00:47:53.930
a big focus of research now in many,

00:47:53.930 --> 00:47:57.900
many business schools, including at Haas.

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:00.980
So companies.

00:48:00.980 --> 00:48:04.100
There's growing evidence that

00:48:04.100 --> 00:48:07.410
the business case for promoting women

00:48:07.410 --> 00:48:09.330
is actually very strong.

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:14.330
So what we have is a
more diverse leadership

00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:17.440
of a company means the
company better reflects

00:48:17.440 --> 00:48:21.590
the profiles of employees and customers.

00:48:21.590 --> 00:48:25.080
It has, there's a lot of
evidence that more diverse teams

00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:26.930
lead to better decisions,

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:29.820
so diversity in teams,
both gender diversity

00:48:29.820 --> 00:48:33.400
and other kinds of diversity
leads to better decisions.

00:48:33.400 --> 00:48:35.680
Companies that are ranked on indicators

00:48:35.680 --> 00:48:39.600
of organizational health, like
how well do people get along,

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:42.600
open communications, trust,

00:48:42.600 --> 00:48:44.750
more where there's greater diversity,

00:48:44.750 --> 00:48:48.820
or greater parity in leadership,

00:48:48.820 --> 00:48:50.600
those companies get ranked

00:48:50.600 --> 00:48:54.400
as having higher organizational health.

00:48:54.400 --> 00:48:57.420
And then what Credit Suisse has reported,

00:48:57.420 --> 00:48:59.040
and others have found the same thing,

00:48:59.040 --> 00:49:02.290
is companies that have more gender parity

00:49:02.290 --> 00:49:05.930
in their pipeline all
the way through the top,

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:09.490
tend to have better financial performance.

00:49:09.490 --> 00:49:12.880
So let me summarize
where we are right now.

00:49:12.880 --> 00:49:17.880
There's a very strong
country level economic case

00:49:18.160 --> 00:49:21.320
that moving towards greater gender parity,

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:25.720
achieving gender equality
in health, education,

00:49:25.720 --> 00:49:28.750
economic engagement and
political empowerment

00:49:30.090 --> 00:49:34.050
have beneficial effects on
national economic performance.

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:37.350
There is a very strong literature,

00:49:37.350 --> 00:49:41.210
and it's become very compelling to read,

00:49:41.210 --> 00:49:44.679
that that is also true at
the level of companies.

00:49:44.679 --> 00:49:47.230
And the biggest global
companies in the world now

00:49:48.070 --> 00:49:51.530
recognize this and are
trying to figure out

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:56.530
how to mobilize more female talent.

00:49:56.820 --> 00:50:00.200
So the country level data suggests

00:50:00.200 --> 00:50:02.400
it's gonna take 81 years to get to parity.

