00:57:18.150 --> 00:57:22.938
This gets to the issue of most jobs today

00:57:22.938 --> 00:57:27.810
do not require a physical
presence all the time

00:57:27.810 --> 00:57:29.200
on a production line,

00:57:29.200 --> 00:57:33.290
and since flexibility turns out
to be of critical importance

00:57:33.290 --> 00:57:37.320
to women, particularly at
certain times in their life,

00:57:37.320 --> 00:57:40.040
organizing the workplace
around flexibility

00:57:40.040 --> 00:57:42.250
is gonna become more and more important.

00:57:42.250 --> 00:57:45.090
So now I'm gonna leave you
with my most fun slide,

00:57:45.090 --> 00:57:47.240
but I wanna say with this slide

00:57:47.240 --> 00:57:52.240
that this reflects the work
ongoing of a group of scholars

00:57:52.810 --> 00:57:56.660
around the country who
are trying to look at

00:57:56.660 --> 00:58:00.500
relevant differences in gender behavior,

00:58:00.500 --> 00:58:03.140
that are relevant to policy makers.

00:58:03.140 --> 00:58:04.630
They're thinking about what can we do

00:58:04.630 --> 00:58:06.720
to promote gender parity,

00:58:06.720 --> 00:58:08.950
or to business leaders who are thinking

00:58:08.950 --> 00:58:11.170
what can we do to promote gender parity.

00:58:11.170 --> 00:58:13.650
You need to know these
kinds of differences

00:58:13.650 --> 00:58:15.390
if you're going to do the right things.

00:58:15.390 --> 00:58:17.313
So these are some of the differences.

00:58:19.730 --> 00:58:23.714
Men show up in study after
study to be more confident.

00:58:23.714 --> 00:58:28.000
In study after study
they turn up to be more,

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:29.908
they like competition more.

00:58:29.908 --> 00:58:32.630
They are willing to negotiate more.

00:58:32.630 --> 00:58:34.440
Women worry about backlashes,

00:58:34.440 --> 00:58:36.080
they worry about stereotypes,

00:58:36.080 --> 00:58:37.440
they're a little worried about,

00:58:37.440 --> 00:58:39.980
when you see these results
of how the students

00:58:39.980 --> 00:58:41.740
evaluated their professors,

00:58:41.740 --> 00:58:43.620
you're a little worried about stereotypes.

00:58:43.620 --> 00:58:45.140
Okay, you're a little worried about being

00:58:45.140 --> 00:58:48.810
the bossy, unfeeling, domineering woman.

00:58:48.810 --> 00:58:51.090
Which if you use the same words for men

00:58:51.090 --> 00:58:56.090
would be the leader,
insightful, inspiring male.

00:58:56.510 --> 00:59:00.306
So these are just a whole
variety of differences,

00:59:00.306 --> 00:59:03.180
and I'll leave you, again,

00:59:03.180 --> 00:59:05.800
we can talk about any one of these,

00:59:05.800 --> 00:59:08.630
but the good news here is that

00:59:08.630 --> 00:59:10.830
scholars around the country,

00:59:10.830 --> 00:59:12.360
and indeed around the world,

00:59:12.360 --> 00:59:15.500
using very sophisticated techniques now,

00:59:15.500 --> 00:59:18.730
are actually confirming, to my mind,

00:59:18.730 --> 00:59:21.710
some things of gender differences which

00:59:21.710 --> 00:59:24.380
anecdotally I heard all my life,

00:59:24.380 --> 00:59:27.420
but actually now I can see
that in experimental settings,

00:59:27.420 --> 00:59:29.660
or in large survey
settings with a lot of data

00:59:29.660 --> 00:59:32.243
and a lot of rigor,
they're being documented.

00:59:33.350 --> 00:59:35.810
So now let me conclude here,

00:59:35.810 --> 00:59:40.760
because I was asked to make
this a little bit personal,

00:59:40.760 --> 00:59:45.310
with some personal
observations about my own life.

00:59:45.310 --> 00:59:46.840
I started with the fact that

00:59:47.900 --> 00:59:50.650
Berkeley was very important to me.

00:59:50.650 --> 00:59:53.950
Academic life is a kind of life

00:59:53.950 --> 00:59:58.710
which does allow you to ramp your time up

00:59:58.710 --> 01:00:00.450
and ramp your time down.

01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:04.430
To opt out a little bit when
your child is really young,

01:00:04.430 --> 01:00:07.530
then to opt back in, figure a year later.

01:00:07.530 --> 01:00:09.620
So there are certain occupations

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:12.550
which are naturally more
flexible than others,

01:00:12.550 --> 01:00:15.210
and university professor, for me,

01:00:15.210 --> 01:00:17.210
I mean I always wanted to
be a university professor,

01:00:17.210 --> 01:00:19.570
not because of that,
but it turned out that

01:00:19.570 --> 01:00:22.313
that was really good, that
was really a big plus.

01:00:23.660 --> 01:00:25.880
But I do wanna say that

01:00:27.670 --> 01:00:29.090
in thinking about my own life,

01:00:29.090 --> 01:00:33.390
first of all, my son
asked me a few years ago,

01:00:33.390 --> 01:00:36.367
he said, "Mom, the women I'm dating

01:00:36.367 --> 01:00:37.707
"want you to write a book because

01:00:37.707 --> 01:00:39.260
"they wanna know how you did it."

01:00:39.260 --> 01:00:41.727
And he said, "And I don't
know how you did it.

01:00:41.727 --> 01:00:44.400
"I was your son, but I have no idea."

01:00:44.400 --> 01:00:46.430
I didn't write the book,

01:00:46.430 --> 01:00:48.330
maybe I should've at that point.

01:00:48.330 --> 01:00:52.150
But I do think that, besides
having a flexible job,

01:00:52.150 --> 01:00:53.820
which would be part of my answer,

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:56.840
being an academic at a
prestigious university

01:00:56.840 --> 01:00:58.210
which was flexible with me

01:00:58.210 --> 01:01:00.690
was a very important
part of what I could do.

01:01:00.690 --> 01:01:03.140
So a workplace designed with flexibility

01:01:03.140 --> 01:01:04.583
in mind is gonna be great.

01:01:06.330 --> 01:01:11.330
But frankly, I also had a
largely stay at home spouse.

01:01:12.260 --> 01:01:15.220
So if you read Sheryl
Sandberg's book Lean In,

01:01:15.220 --> 01:01:17.950
she has two lessons in her book.

01:01:17.950 --> 01:01:21.020
One is lean in, negotiate,

01:01:21.020 --> 01:01:23.240
say what you're willing
to do to take that job,

01:01:23.240 --> 01:01:24.700
don't let yourself be overlooked,

01:01:24.700 --> 01:01:27.880
all those things about
negotiating, competition,

01:01:27.880 --> 01:01:30.540
those things are part of leaning in.

01:01:30.540 --> 01:01:33.163
She also says marry the right person.

01:01:33.163 --> 01:01:33.996
(audience laughter)

01:01:33.996 --> 01:01:35.870
Now I wanna say, I do think,

01:01:35.870 --> 01:01:37.860
I don't know how you manage
to figure this all out,

01:01:37.860 --> 01:01:41.420
is there like some big
job interview that you do,

01:01:41.420 --> 01:01:44.560
anyway, spouses really do matter

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:46.530
because of all the things
we talked about earlier.

01:01:46.530 --> 01:01:47.460
Partnerships matter.

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:51.420
I think Esther and Harvey's
partnership really matters.

01:01:51.420 --> 01:01:53.180
You can see this, one of the things

01:01:53.180 --> 01:01:55.700
that's really interesting is

01:01:55.700 --> 01:01:57.720
if you look at Catalyst,

01:01:57.720 --> 01:01:59.920
Catalyst is a very good
source of information

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:03.580
on gender differences in businesses.

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:07.450
So 75% of men holding
top business positions

01:02:07.450 --> 01:02:10.040
in the United States have spouses

01:02:10.040 --> 01:02:12.110
or partners who are not employed.

01:02:12.110 --> 01:02:14.060
75%.

01:02:14.060 --> 01:02:15.670
Okay, not employed.

01:02:15.670 --> 01:02:18.570
75% of women holding similar positions

01:02:18.570 --> 01:02:21.863
have spouses or partners
who are employed full-time.

01:02:23.360 --> 01:02:25.540
Balance, balance, balance.

01:02:25.540 --> 01:02:28.100
I had a spouse who was working from home,

01:02:28.100 --> 01:02:31.930
and so that made my life
considerably easier.

01:02:31.930 --> 01:02:34.990
And I, in thinking about what lessons

01:02:34.990 --> 01:02:35.970
I would have for people,

01:02:35.970 --> 01:02:39.440
the lessons are flexible
career, flexible spouse,

01:02:39.440 --> 01:02:40.580
spouse who works at home.

01:02:40.580 --> 01:02:43.223
They're not generally applicable, I'd say.

01:02:44.170 --> 01:02:47.200
However, even in that setting,

01:02:47.200 --> 01:02:51.440
the job I had that was most inflexible

01:02:51.440 --> 01:02:54.420
was working for Bill Clinton.

01:02:54.420 --> 01:02:55.700
Any working for any president,

01:02:55.700 --> 01:02:57.630
there's no flexibility in that.

01:02:57.630 --> 01:02:58.520
No flexibility.

01:02:58.520 --> 01:03:01.970
So that job was a job that I had,

01:03:01.970 --> 01:03:04.370
that my husband had, that my son had.

01:03:04.370 --> 01:03:05.860
It was our job.

01:03:05.860 --> 01:03:08.330
It was a family job.

01:03:08.330 --> 01:03:10.450
At the end of four years,

01:03:10.450 --> 01:03:13.670
the two other people who
had the job besides me,

01:03:13.670 --> 01:03:16.007
said, "We're done with this job.

01:03:16.007 --> 01:03:17.987
"We're going back to Berkeley.

01:03:17.987 --> 01:03:20.387
"You're welcome to come with us."

01:03:21.450 --> 01:03:23.430
Now, I decided to come with them.

01:03:23.430 --> 01:03:24.530
I could've stayed.

01:03:24.530 --> 01:03:26.750
I actually had the opportunity

01:03:26.750 --> 01:03:28.870
to get a cabinet level position,

01:03:28.870 --> 01:03:31.270
and I told the president I was going.

01:03:31.270 --> 01:03:34.550
But this is about the
nature of jobs, by the way,

01:03:34.550 --> 01:03:37.020
because I wasn't the
only person who did that.

01:03:37.020 --> 01:03:39.410
Bob Reich, who's a professor at Cal,

01:03:39.410 --> 01:03:40.410
and a good friend of mine,

01:03:40.410 --> 01:03:43.280
and my husband happens to be
out to dinner with him tonight,

01:03:43.280 --> 01:03:45.170
Bob Reich and his family went through

01:03:45.170 --> 01:03:49.390
exactly the same discussion
at exactly the same time.

01:03:49.390 --> 01:03:51.640
And Bob and I both left government.

01:03:51.640 --> 01:03:53.770
So there are certain careers,

01:03:53.770 --> 01:03:57.270
and certain inflexibilities
where you have to

01:03:57.270 --> 01:04:00.030
essentially say, this is a family,

01:04:00.030 --> 01:04:03.510
and families have to balance
over the lifetime of a family

01:04:03.510 --> 01:04:08.510
how you deal with spousal
issues of careers.

01:04:09.390 --> 01:04:12.210
Last night, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg was being interviewed,

01:04:12.210 --> 01:04:15.977
and she said, "You know,
when I was younger,

01:04:15.977 --> 01:04:18.987
"my husband wanted to make
it in this New York law firm

01:04:18.987 --> 01:04:20.440
"in five years, in record time."

01:04:20.440 --> 01:04:22.830
She said, "I did everything
so he could do that."

01:04:22.830 --> 01:04:23.747
And she said, "Since then,

01:04:23.747 --> 01:04:25.293
"he's been doing everything for me."

01:04:25.293 --> 01:04:26.630
(laughter)

01:04:26.630 --> 01:04:28.510
That was the balance
they did in their life.

01:04:28.510 --> 01:04:32.560
So there are very important
personal parts of this

01:04:32.560 --> 01:04:37.560
that you can't, a workplace
can design a flexible job.

01:04:38.770 --> 01:04:41.200
But some jobs are not gonna be flexible,

01:04:41.200 --> 01:04:43.330
and therefore the flexibility's
gonna have to come

01:04:43.330 --> 01:04:45.780
in the family and the
expectations of the family.

01:04:46.660 --> 01:04:51.660
So I think that leaning
in is important for women.

01:04:52.350 --> 01:04:55.950
Leaning in is important for their spouses.

01:04:55.950 --> 01:04:58.470
Leaning in is also
important for companies,

01:04:58.470 --> 01:04:59.687
that is, companies have to say,

01:04:59.687 --> 01:05:03.837
"What can I do to make my workplace

01:05:03.837 --> 01:05:08.800
"a more flexible, gender
parity supporting workplace?"

01:05:08.800 --> 01:05:10.500
Companies have to lean in.

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:12.440
And of course, governments
have to lean in.

01:05:12.440 --> 01:05:14.280
And this is where I hope,

01:05:14.280 --> 01:05:17.070
the US is not at all a leader here.

01:05:17.070 --> 01:05:18.860
Absolutely not a leader here

01:05:18.860 --> 01:05:20.580
compared to other developed countries.

01:05:20.580 --> 01:05:22.380
I mean, just think about it this way.

01:05:22.380 --> 01:05:27.260
In France you get, I think,
a month and a half off

01:05:27.260 --> 01:05:30.140
from work before your child is born,

01:05:30.140 --> 01:05:31.460
two and a half months after,

01:05:31.460 --> 01:05:36.460
and then you get full pay
for working 80% of the time.

01:05:36.690 --> 01:05:38.080
That's how they've handled it.

01:05:38.080 --> 01:05:39.200
Different societies handle it,

01:05:39.200 --> 01:05:42.920
but they have very
supportive family policies,

01:05:42.920 --> 01:05:44.720
and the US does not.

01:05:44.720 --> 01:05:46.350
And as a consequence of that,

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:47.780
one of the things that's happened is

01:05:47.780 --> 01:05:50.610
our labor force participation rates

01:05:50.610 --> 01:05:52.620
are no longer leading the world,

01:05:52.620 --> 01:05:55.850
and our wage gap numbers are
no longer leading the world.

01:05:55.850 --> 01:05:58.650
That is, we're not showing,

01:05:58.650 --> 01:06:00.150
some people say that what's happened

01:06:00.150 --> 01:06:02.150
is we achieved a lot of increasing

01:06:02.150 --> 01:06:03.890
gender parity for a while,

01:06:03.890 --> 01:06:05.440
and then we kinda hit a wall,

01:06:05.440 --> 01:06:07.520
we hit a wall around 2000,

01:06:07.520 --> 01:06:10.550
and since that time labor
force participation rates

01:06:10.550 --> 01:06:12.900
for women in the US have been coming down,

01:06:12.900 --> 01:06:16.840
and the wage gap has stabilized.

01:06:16.840 --> 01:06:19.300
So women were making progress
at closing the wage gap,

01:06:19.300 --> 01:06:21.210
but then it just stopped.

01:06:21.210 --> 01:06:22.870
So we need to think about,

01:06:22.870 --> 01:06:24.540
from a policy point of view,

01:06:24.540 --> 01:06:26.670
if we're committed to
greater gender parity,

01:06:26.670 --> 01:06:27.860
what to do in the United States.

01:06:27.860 --> 01:06:31.530
So why don't I leave it
policy, family, companies.

01:06:31.530 --> 01:06:33.620
There are great benefits to be had

01:06:33.620 --> 01:06:34.900
from promoting gender parity.

01:06:34.900 --> 01:06:36.480
There's lots to be done.

01:06:36.480 --> 01:06:38.560
When we do it, we have to understand

01:06:38.560 --> 01:06:40.480
that there are these
underlying differences

01:06:40.480 --> 01:06:41.500
in how people behave,

01:06:41.500 --> 01:06:44.820
and we have to shape our
institutions accordingly.

01:06:44.820 --> 01:06:45.974
Thank you.

01:06:45.974 --> 01:06:48.974
(audience applause)

01:06:59.150 --> 01:07:01.390
- Thank you very much for a talk that was

01:07:01.390 --> 01:07:04.110
not only inspiring, but also wise.

01:07:04.110 --> 01:07:05.110
- Thank you.

01:07:05.950 --> 01:07:07.660
- I'd love to dominate the questions,

01:07:07.660 --> 01:07:10.530
but I know there are lots
of people in the audience

01:07:10.530 --> 01:07:12.590
who also have questions.

01:07:12.590 --> 01:07:14.380
Because we're taping this,

01:07:14.380 --> 01:07:15.970
one of the wonderful things we do

01:07:15.970 --> 01:07:19.480
is record these lectures and post them

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:24.480
so that people can review
them for posterity.

01:07:24.510 --> 01:07:27.280
I'd ask anybody who was questions

01:07:27.280 --> 01:07:29.120
to come up to the mic here

01:07:29.120 --> 01:07:32.140
so that their questions can be heard.

01:07:32.140 --> 01:07:33.963
So, yes please start.

01:07:41.120 --> 01:07:41.953
- Thank you.

01:07:41.953 --> 01:07:44.670
Laura, your points hit
home on so many levels.

01:07:44.670 --> 01:07:47.210
I'm a headhunter, I do executive search

01:07:47.210 --> 01:07:50.053
for software start-up
companies in Silicon Valley.

01:07:52.661 --> 01:07:56.370
I have for years been saying
exactly what you said up there,

01:07:56.370 --> 01:07:57.870
that women won't negotiate,

01:07:57.870 --> 01:08:00.930
that women won't take
chances, they're risk averse.

01:08:00.930 --> 01:08:03.130
They don't wanna be entrepreneurs,

01:08:03.130 --> 01:08:05.240
they'd rather work for somebody
else, they don't want that.

01:08:05.240 --> 01:08:08.330
They won't go out on a limb,
they don't have the confidence.

01:08:08.330 --> 01:08:13.330
So what can I do when female after female,

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:15.560
and it takes a long time to find

01:08:15.560 --> 01:08:18.440
a really qualified female executive,

01:08:18.440 --> 01:08:21.700
turns me down for an offer because

01:08:21.700 --> 01:08:24.070
they don't wanna trade
off maybe a little bit

01:08:24.070 --> 01:08:27.590
of cash compensation for
equity in the company,

01:08:27.590 --> 01:08:30.310
or because they feel that they've reached

01:08:30.310 --> 01:08:32.730
a point of prominence in a large company

01:08:32.730 --> 01:08:35.597
and think to themselves, "If I leave,

01:08:35.597 --> 01:08:40.070
"I won't feel that status
that I've attained."

01:08:40.070 --> 01:08:42.360
- So look, I don't think,

01:08:42.360 --> 01:08:43.940
I think to some extent,

01:08:43.940 --> 01:08:45.950
particularly on these kinds of things,

01:08:45.950 --> 01:08:50.950
I think the most you can do
is point out to individuals,

01:08:51.250 --> 01:08:52.930
whether they're male or female,

01:08:52.930 --> 01:08:56.450
that, though they're making a choice,

01:08:56.450 --> 01:08:59.080
they should understand that that choice

01:08:59.080 --> 01:09:04.080
may reflect a broader
set of cultural norms

01:09:04.240 --> 01:09:05.730
that they've absorbed without even

01:09:05.730 --> 01:09:07.080
realizing they've absorbed them.

01:09:07.080 --> 01:09:10.920
I mean, you both have to
give people the opportunity

01:09:10.920 --> 01:09:13.590
to say I'm a more risk averse person,

01:09:13.590 --> 01:09:17.270
but I think by letting people know,

01:09:17.270 --> 01:09:19.550
you know women are more risk averse.

01:09:19.550 --> 01:09:21.520
If you're a mentor and you're saying

01:09:21.520 --> 01:09:22.920
women tend to be more risk averse,

01:09:22.920 --> 01:09:27.320
are you sure this is, did you know that?

01:09:27.320 --> 01:09:30.320
Do you feel that maybe
you should take this risk?

01:09:30.320 --> 01:09:32.270
It's a little bit more talking to them

01:09:32.270 --> 01:09:35.450
about the evidence, and making
it a little less personal.

01:09:35.450 --> 01:09:36.630
But at the end of the day,

01:09:36.630 --> 01:09:40.140
I don't think you can,
if that's their decision,

01:09:40.140 --> 01:09:42.880
it is their decision, it
absolutely is their decision.

01:09:42.880 --> 01:09:44.990
Then what you can do
for the kind of careers

01:09:44.990 --> 01:09:47.730
you're talking about, is actually work on

01:09:48.910 --> 01:09:51.750
why women choose the majors they choose.

01:09:51.750 --> 01:09:56.750
Or why they, do they not
see role models that,

01:09:58.010 --> 01:10:00.760
if there are not enough
role models out there

01:10:00.760 --> 01:10:04.560
for them to see, then the
risk to them seems higher,

01:10:04.560 --> 01:10:06.460
so they're less likely to do it.

01:10:06.460 --> 01:10:08.123
So in a sense you have to say,

01:10:09.730 --> 01:10:12.980
choose the riskier major,
choose the riskier career

01:10:12.980 --> 01:10:14.510
because you could be a model.

01:10:14.510 --> 01:10:16.850
And you can't expect to see
a lot of models out there

01:10:16.850 --> 01:10:19.240
because there are not yet.

01:10:19.240 --> 01:10:22.980
But I don't know, I tend
in these kinds of things

01:10:22.980 --> 01:10:24.760
when I'm talking to young women

01:10:24.760 --> 01:10:27.500
just to point out that they exist.

01:10:27.500 --> 01:10:30.943
And so I've talked to
women who actually said,

01:10:32.530 --> 01:10:33.410
a woman recently was talking about

01:10:33.410 --> 01:10:35.410
how she felt she was not being paid

01:10:35.410 --> 01:10:37.210
appropriately at a venture capital firm,

01:10:37.210 --> 01:10:39.620
and I said well, have you gone in

01:10:39.620 --> 01:10:40.897
and talked to them about it?

01:10:40.897 --> 01:10:42.740
"Well no, I don't feel
comfortable doing it."

01:10:42.740 --> 01:10:44.910
And then I say you actually have to do it.

01:10:44.910 --> 01:10:48.655
You have to do it because you're
just confirming the notion

01:10:48.655 --> 01:10:53.655
of the unwillingness to
negotiate actually will affect

01:10:55.490 --> 01:10:56.770
how you're paid over time.

01:10:56.770 --> 01:10:57.980
That's just the way it is.

01:10:57.980 --> 01:10:58.840
Those are the norms.

01:10:58.840 --> 01:11:01.257
Until the companies themselves say,

01:11:01.257 --> 01:11:03.827
"I understand that
there's this difference,

01:11:03.827 --> 01:11:07.177
"therefore I'm gonna go
out and actually not,

01:11:07.177 --> 01:11:09.537
"I'm gonna evaluate men
and women in such a way

01:11:09.537 --> 01:11:13.530
"that negotiating differences
don't affect outcomes."

01:11:13.530 --> 01:11:16.530
That would be the
company's solution to that.

01:11:16.530 --> 01:11:18.440
For the individual solution to that,

01:11:18.440 --> 01:11:21.600
it's gotta be to recognize
that these differences exist,

01:11:21.600 --> 01:11:23.870
and that it's worth going in.

01:11:23.870 --> 01:11:26.927
Because if you go in, see I
think you can go in and say,

01:11:26.927 --> 01:11:31.197
"By the way, I'm here,
and the CEO of Microsoft

01:11:31.197 --> 01:11:33.297
"said something and
it's actually not true.

01:11:33.297 --> 01:11:35.857
"Women in general are not being recognized

01:11:35.857 --> 01:11:37.217
"for their performance,

01:11:37.217 --> 01:11:39.280
"and I think I wanna bring
it to your attention."

01:11:39.280 --> 01:11:41.150
You could actually bring a
whole bunch of this evidence

01:11:41.150 --> 01:11:43.110
into the room with you.

01:11:43.110 --> 01:11:48.110
So, but look, I don't have a solution,

01:11:48.190 --> 01:11:53.190
because women do, even
though it may be the case

01:11:54.330 --> 01:11:56.380
that a lot of the women
you're dealing with

01:11:56.380 --> 01:12:01.380
are women who have been affected
by these cultural norms,

01:12:01.540 --> 01:12:03.880
and if they could sort
of break out of them

01:12:03.880 --> 01:12:06.070
and behave differently,
they have been affected,

01:12:06.070 --> 01:12:08.000
so I don't know how to change that.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:09.600
I don't know how to change that.

